X Marks the Spot: A Landlubberd's Guide to Pirate Nation

Chris Davis

3 days ago   14 min read

Key Takeaways

  • Pirate Nation is a pirate-themed, fully onchain RPG from game studio Proof of Play that blends semi-casual gameplay with the landmark economic mechanisms of Web3 gaming.
  • The game has processed hundreds of millions of transactions across over 300,000 addresses, overcoming the scalability limitations that have historically hindered fully onchain games.
  • Pirate Nations go-to-market strategy aligns with major gaming industry trends, including mobile-first development and a focus on user-generated content (UGC).
  • While Pirate Nation is still in the early stages of its development, adoption metrics point to sustained engagement among its core player base, providing a solid foundation for future growth and retention.

Introduction

2024 has seen a surge in Web3 gaming adoption, hitting a peak of 7.94 million onchain active addresses on October 12, according to Footprint Analytics. Despite this growth, most blockchain games remain only partially onchain, with core gameplay and state still managed on centralized servers.

Fully onchain games (FOCGs), which host all game logic and state directly on the blockchain, offer a new paradigm with benefits like perpetual gameplay, permissionless extensibility, and interoperability between game worlds.

Despite their advantages, FOCGs have yet to gain significant adoption outside of niche audiences. High transaction costs, slow block times, and UX challenges have historically prevented FOCGs from achieving the level of scalability required to form a robust player base.

However, as infrastructure becomes increasingly efficient, will FOCGs soon be able to overcome these challenges and reach wider audiences?

Pirate Nation, a pirate-themed role-playing game (RPG) by Proof of Play, may be the first to break through these barriers. Built on two high-throughput chains developed with Arbitrums Orbit Stack, Pirate Nation has already processed over 350 million transactions across more than 300,000 addresses. While the game is still in its early stages of development, its positioning within growing industry trends, coupled with an engaged core community, sets the stage for strong future growth.

In this report, well cover the defining features of FOCGs, the infrastructure advancements that power Pirate Nation, gameplay and in-game economics, growth strategy, adoption thus far, and what lies ahead.

An Overview of FOCGs

Most Web3 games today primarily rely on the blockchain to support the ownership and trading of in-game assets. For these games, core gameplay logic and state are stored offchain on centralized servers, with only the assets themselves stored onchain. By contrast, fully onchain games store and execute all game contentlogic, state, and assetsdirectly on the blockchain.

For instance, a partially onchain Web3 Pokmon game might store only the Pokmon as NFTs. In a fully onchain version, however, all battle logic would run within smart contracts, with each move, health update, and match outcome executed and stored onchain.

By putting the entirety of the games state and logic onchain, FOCGs enable:

  • Perpetual Gameplay: As long as the blockchain exists, so does the game, remaining accessible to players indefinitely.
  • Permissionless Extensibility: Developers can build upon games by calling functions from existing contracts, enabling continuous community-driven growth.
  • Identity Interoperability: Attributes from one game, like skill levels or quests completed, can be read onchain and incorporated into other games.

Combined with gaming-adjacent sectors like DeFi, these properties lay the foundation for novel gameplay mechanics and creative business models within a perpetually expanding gameplay universe.

While FOCGs hold immense creative potential, the question remains: Can they work at scale?

Solving the FOCG Infrastructure Problem

Making a game fully onchain necessitates submitting frequent transactions to the blockchain, which, without efficient infrastructure, can create a user experience plagued by constant signature requests, high gas fees, and significant latency as transactions settle. On the developer side, the lack of familiar tools in this new environment limits the total addressable market of developers willing to engage with fully onchain game development.

For these reasons, Proof of Play, the game studio behind Pirate Nation, has developed an array of infrastructure advancements for onchain gaming that unlock the full creative potential of FOCGs.

The Multichain

Pirate Nation runs on the Proof of Play Multichain, which consists of Apex Chain and Boss Chain, two AnyTrust Layer 3s utilizing Arbitrums Orbit Stack. AnyTrust significantly reduces fees by posting data offchain to a data availability committee. While this development decision accepts a mild trust assumption, the tradeoff has enabled Pirate Nation to reduce transaction fees from hundreds of GWei per transaction on Polygon to just 0.01 GWei per transaction.

Gasless, Signless Transactions

Since Pirate Nations launch in December 2022, the Proof of Play team has provided solutions to two major pain points of FOCGs: wallet signatures and gas fees.

When players first connect their main wallet to Pirate Nation, a Game Wallet a custodial, in-browser wallet is created to perform in-game transactions on behalf of the main wallet. After an initial signature, this wallet can autonomously handle gameplay actions such as crafting, quests, and other in-game functions defined strictly within the games contracts. By limiting transactions to functions in the games contracts, the main wallets funds are protected even if the Game Wallet is compromised. Furthermore, assets earned in-game are sent directly to the main wallet, bypassing the game wallet entirely.

Gasless transactions are enabled through EIP-2771, an ERC standard that allows transactions to be forwarded through a third-party relayer that pays for gas on behalf of the sender. While transactions on the Multichain only cost a few cents on average, removing the need for users to hold funds removes multiple points of friction in the player journey, such as swapping, transferring, and bridging assets.

Onchain Game Engine, Entity-Component System (ECS) and Editor

Proof of Plays onchain game engine, ECS, and editor are key elements of their developer toolkit that fast-tracks the development of onchain games. Composed of hundreds of smart contracts, the onchain game engine provides developers with core configurable game systems which act as the foundation for creative development.

The ECS and editor are no-code solutions that further facilitate the development process, enabling non-engineers to easily edit and add game data. As Proof of Play expands its ecosystem, these advancements will be a massive asset for driving the acquisition of seasoned FOCG developers and developers new to onchain gaming.

Pirate Nation: Gameplay & Economics

Game Play

Pirate Nation is a semi-casual RPG where players assemble a crew of pirates, construct ships to explore the Infinite Isles, embark on quests and bounties, battle against sea monsters, and compete against other players to climb the leaderboard.

While Pirate Nation frequently releases new gameplay, the games core loop involves many landmark characteristics of RPGs.

Combat

Pirate Nations card-based combat system includes both player versus player (PvP) combat as well as player versus environment (PvE) combat. The combat system employs a classic rock-paper-scissors mechanic by which certain card elements have advantages and disadvantages compared to other card elements. This combat style is similar to games like Pokmon, where a fire-type Pokmon has an innate advantage over grass-type Pokmon. Cards used in combat are acquired by leveling up pirates and building more powerful ships.

Exploration

In exploration mode, players can sail their ships across the sea, exploring procedurally generated islands in search of resources. The configuration of islands changes on a shared world map every 12 hours. When a new map launches, players often share the coordinates of monsters and unique islands with other players in the Pirate Nation Discord, introducing a social element to gameplay.

Quests

Embarking on quests enables players to acquire resources and level up their Pirate. The resources earned from quests are essential for building ships and progressing to higher-level quests. Though quests dont require any real-time action and run in the background on a timer, there is an element of strategy in deciding which quests to pursue based on a players current needs.

Crafting

Resources gathered through exploration and quests can be combined to make higher-tier resources and items, which unlock more profitable quests. Leveling up exploration skills such as mining, harvesting, and gathering allows players to unlock rarer resources required in more advanced crafting recipes. Basic resources can also be converted into "stockpiles" and sold to other players on the Proof of Play Marketplace.

Trading

Ships, stockpiles, and various in-game items are NFTs that players can export from the game and trade peer-to-peer for ETH on the Proof of Play Marketplace. To export items from the game to the marketplace, players must first obtain a Trade License, awarded upon reaching Command Rank 10.

Pirate Nations Economy

Currencies

Alongside the NFTs that players can export and sell on the Proof of Play Marketplace, the Pirate Nation economy is driven by three fungible currencies: $PGLD, Gems, and $PIRATE.

$PGLD is the primary in-game currency, used for various in-game actions such as upgrading ships, converting resources into stockpiles for external trading, and dispatching Pirates on bounties. Until reaching Rank 10, players earn Marks instead of $PGLD; these serve the same in-game functions and are automatically converted to $PGLD once Rank 10 is achieved.

To maintain balance, $PGLD has various sinksactivities like bounties, ship upgrades, crafting stockpiles, and hard mode PvE battles that remove $PGLD from circulation. Conversely, faucets such as quest rewards, treasure chests, and resource sales introduce new $PGLD into the economy. Alongside factors like energy regeneration and leveling rates, these mechanisms manage resource flow to ensure steady progression throughout the game.

$PIRATE is the games primary ERC-20 token. Right now, $PIRATE's involvement is mostly limited to staking, purchasing Gems, and end-of-season rewards, but as more utility is introduced, well likely see a stronger impact on player progression and gameplay.

Gems are a non-transferable currency that can only be purchased with $PIRATE. Gems allow players to accelerate gameplay, topping off energy or speeding up quest timers. Additionally, Gems can be used to purchase more free-to-play (F2P) Gen1 Pirates, enabling players to undertake additional bounties and improve their combat decks. The development team regularly adjusts Gem pricing to manage supply and demandeither to encourage gem usage (burning Gems) or incentivize purchasing (minting Gems).

Founders Pirates

The Founders Pirates collection, Pirate Nations genesis NFT set, includes 9,999 PFP-style pirates that offer a range of in-game advantages. While every player receives a free-to-play soulbound "Gen1" Pirate upon joining, these Gen0 NFTs unlock exclusive bounties, reward chests, and other evolving perks, establishing them as valuable assets within the games ecosystem. Early adopters who held a Founders Pirate during the games $PIRATE airdrop campaign benefited from a points multiplier, giving them an edge in accumulating rewards.

A similar mechanism is in place today with Pirate staking, where stakers earn additional "Proof of Play points, likely a signal for future airdrop eligibility. This structure positions the Founders Pirates as a central component of the games reward economy, adding value for long-term holders as new benefits unfold.

Balancing the Economy

Maintaining economic balance is critical for any game economy, but the Web3 layer brings an added challenge: speculation. External trading pressures amplify economic fluctuations, making sustainable resource balancing more complex.

Should the Pirate Nation economy experience significant instability, the team has built-in levers to manage balance, such as adjusting energy regeneration, leveling rates, item drop frequencies, and crafting requirements. These tools provide a range of options to keep the in-game economy resilient to internal imbalances and external market forces.

Go-to-Market Strategy

Pirate Nation's go-to-market strategy aligns with broad industry trends, such as the continued expansion of mobile gaming and the rise of user-generated content (UGC). Throughout the games development, the team has taken a "build in public" approach, regularly releasing updates and engaging directly with the community to gather feedback and reward in-game participation.

Mobile Gaming

Approximately 80% of gamers play on mobile, generating nearly $90 billion annually and representing 49% of global gaming revenue. While Pirate Nation is currently limited to browser, the game was designed to become a mobile-first experience. The team plans to expand Pirate Nation to mobile sometime in 2025 and has already begun optimizing game features to prepare for the transition.

User Generated Content

In recent years, user-generated content (UGC) has emerged as a powerful driver of network effects in gaming. As more players join, the game evolves into an increasingly attractive distribution channel for creators, whose contributions lead to fresh and engaging gameplay that, in turn, attracts even more players. One of the most notable success stories of UGC is Fortnite's introduction of "Creative," a sandbox mode where players design games and experiences for others. In 2023, Epic Games reported that 40% of all playtime is spent exploring spaces created by other users, underscoring UGC's significant impact on user engagement.

Since its inception, Pirate Nation has prioritized UGC as part of its long-term strategy. This focus is reflected in its developer acquisition approach and design choices, such as the planned release of an SDK and its Voxel-style graphics, which make UGC more accessible to less experienced creators.

Building in Public

In December 2022, the team released Pirate Nations first public update, along with a blog post outlining the changes. Since then, theyve shipped 94 updates on a weekly cadence. By releasing updates at this pace, the team can gather immediate community feedback, gaining a clearer understanding of which changes resonate and which dont. This approach has strengthened relationships with their core communitya critical factor for sustained growth in an industry known for low retention rates.

Adoption

While Pirate Nation doesnt report daily active addresses directly, Helikas dashboard offers enough data to roughly estimate the total active player count each day by summing daily players minting $PGLD and those minting Marks - the $PGLD equivalent that players earn before reaching Command Rank 10.

Between Q2 2024 and early Q3, the game grew rapidly, expanding from approximately 3,000 active addresses in March to over 80,000 by early July. This growth was largely driven by players minting Marks, which is expected given that it typically takes months to reach Rank 10 and begin minting $PGLD. Since July, the player count has declined by about 33% to around 53,000. This is likely due in part to post-airdrop churn following the $PIRATE TGE in mid-June, and a crackdown on multiaccounting in late-July.

Interestingly, most of this decline has come from players minting Marks, while those minting $PGLD have increased steadily from 4,000 to 20,000. This suggests that although the influx of new players has slowed, many existing players have continued engaging and progressing to higher ranks since the July peak. If Pirate Nation can retain this core community over time and reignite incremental demand, it holds strong potential for breakout success with new audiences drawn to its active and committed player base.

Risks

Limited TAM for Onchain UGC

While UGC has proven to be an effective growth strategy in Web2, the total addressable market for smart contract developers is significantly smaller than that for traditional game developers. This narrower pool makes reaching a tipping point that drives network effects more challenging, likely requiring additional resources and targeted efforts toward developer acquisition.

Economic Instability

Proof of Play points currently serve as a pseudo-sink for $PIRATE, mitigating sell pressure on the token. However, this mechanism may pose future economic stability risks. Post-airdrop, players may liquidate their holdings, exerting sustained downward pressure on $PIRATE's value. If $PIRATE begins to play a more impactful role in Pirate Nation's in-game economy, such a trend could destabilize core economic mechanisms, disrupt earnings, and significantly reduce player retention. To mitigate the impact of removing this sink, it is crucial to establish additional sinks in advance.

Low Retention

While Proof of Play has made strides in expanding its ecosystem, retention risk remains a concern for individual games. This is especially true for play-to-earn titles, where a portion of the player base is primarily focused on earning. As the development community grows and extensions are launched, this risk may diminish, but it remains a key metric to monitor closely in these early stages.

Conclusion

Through Pirate Nation, Proof of Play has shown that scaling fully onchain games (FOCGs) to millions of players is becoming a realistic possibility with advancing infrastructure. The consistent engagement from Pirate Nations core community, robust infrastructure, and a go-to-market strategy that aligns with accelerating gaming industry trends position it as a strong contender for becoming the first widely adopted FOCG. Moreover, the teams commitment to frequent updates and active community engagement adds even more optimism than their long-term roadmap alone. Like all Web3 games, Pirate Nation faces risks as it scales, but the proactive approach demonstrated in its early stages suggests that the team is well-prepared to address and mitigate future challenges if they emerge.
